@@rThe Scorched Wastes@@N

  Not merely another desert. The Scorched Wastes are the @@rburn scar@@N
of a legal-cosmic system failure: the place where oasis water-law,
pyramid sovereignty doctrine, and eclipse ritual engineering overlapped
and catastrophically ruptured.

  In older records this region appears as the @@yMeridian Intake March@@N --
a managed corridor of toll pavilions, cistern regulators, and charter
stations. Modern travelers see only dunes, venom pits, raiders, and
ritual ruins because the corridor's institutions were not simply
abandoned. They were @@rthermally and metaphysically overprinted@@N.

  The decisive event was the failed @@rNinth Meridian Rite@@N, an attempt to
fuse solar measurement and underworld descent authority into one
governing ritual. Surface meridian markers, deep hydraulic voids, and
funerary script matrices desynchronized at culmination. Heat surged
through dry channels meant for water. Pressure inverted in the cistern
regulators. The result was a sustained burn wave: dune glassing,
structural collapse, and undead administrative persistence.

  Three factions contest the wreckage. @@eCharter Remnants@@N -- descendants
of intake clerks and ration auditors -- value records and seals over
combat, treating armed adventurers as unregistered caravans and issuing
warnings before hostility. @@rDune Host Reavers@@N are post-collapse
logistics predators who inherited route knowledge from ruined intake
records, ambushing near marker fields and broken weighbridges.
@@dSynod Eclipse Cells@@N regard the Wastes as a holy proof-site where
failed synthesis can be corrected, staging mock tribunals and
witness-burning rites.

  Beneath the glass and ash, the old infrastructure persists: verdict
halls inhabited by revenants, toll stones recut as curses, ration seals
worn by raiders. The Wastes are a warning to both oasis pragmatists
and pyramid absolutists -- proof of what happens when incompatible
legal and theological systems are forced to operate simultaneously
on failing infrastructure.

  @@dWater memory outlives water presence.@@N Law persists after legitimacy
dies. Administrative tools become ritual weapons under scarcity.
Every room in the Wastes shows at least one trace of former purpose
and one trace of post-catastrophe reuse.
